48","1120–Male":"1120–Overleden","1120–Female":"1120–Overleden","1248":"1248","1168":"1168","1200":"1200","1120":"1120","1140":"1140","Thorpe Manor, Tattershall, Lincolnshire, England":"Tattershall, Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Ashwellthorpe, Norfolk, England":"Ashwellthorpe, Norfolk, England","Thorpe, Lincolnshire, England":"Thorpe St Peter, Lincolnshire, England"},"en":{"1140–1200":"1140–1200","–Female":"Deceased","1168–1248":"1168–1248","1120–Male":"1120–Deceased","1120–Female":"1120–Deceased","1248":"1248","1168":"1168","1200":"1200","1120":"1120","1140":"1140","Thorpe Manor, Tattershall, Lincolnshire, England":"Tattershall, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Ashwellthorpe, Norfolk, England":"Ashwellthorpe, Norfolk, England","Thorpe, Lincolnshire, England":"Thorpe St Peter, Lincolnshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Thorpe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly Yorkshire and Lancashire): from Middle English <i>thorp(e)</i> ‘village, hamlet, farmstead’ (Old Norse, Old English <i>thorp</i> ‘secondary settlement’). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived in such a settlement, or habitational, for someone from any of several places called Thorp(e), which are most frequent in Yorkshire, the Midlands, and East Anglia. Compare   Throop  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Trupp","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Hermann, Reinhold.","English (Herefordshire and Monmouthshire): variant of   Thorpe  , or from a place so named, such as Thrupp (Berkshire, Gloucestershire, Oxfordshire), Thrupe (Somerset), Throop (Dorset, Hampshire, Somerset), and Throope (Wiltshire).","Altered form of German   Trapp  ."]},{"name":"Throop","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>throp</i> ‘village, hamlet, farmstead’ (Old Norse, Old English <i>throp</i> ‘secondary settlement’). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived in such a settlement, or habitational, for someone from Throop in Hampshire, Throope in Wiltshire, Thrup in Oxfordshire, or any of the places called Thrupp in Berkshire, Gloucestershire, and Northamptonshire. Compare   Thorpe  ."]},{"name":"Tharpe","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Thorpe  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Thorp","meanings":["English (mainly Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Thorpe  .","Scandinavian: variant of   Torp  ."]},{"name":"Troup","meanings":["Scottish (eastern): habitational name from a place in the parish of Gamrie, near Banff. The placename is unexplained, perhaps a Pictish cognate of Welsh <i>trwp</i> ‘vessel, dish, basin’.","Possibly also English, a metathesized form of   Thorpe  ."]},{"name":"Tharp","meanings":["English: variant of   Thorpe  ."]}]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Hugh John de Thorpe was born in 1140, in Tattershall, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert de Thorpe, was 21 and his mother, Eda De Thorpe, was 21. He married Unknown. He died in 1200, in Thorpe St Peter, Lincolnshire, England, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1140–1200":"1140–1200","–Female":"Surnud","1168–1248":"1168–1248","1120–Male":"1120–Surnud","1120–Female":"1120–Surnud","1248":"1248","1168":"1168","1200":"1200","1120":"1120","1140":"1140","Thorpe Manor, Tattershall, Lincolnshire, England":"Tattershall, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ashwellthorpe, Norfolk, England":"Ashwellthorpe, Norfolk, England","Thorpe, Lincolnshire, England":"Thorpe St Peter, Lincolnshire, England"},"fi":{"1140–1200":"1140–1200","–Female":"Kuollut","1168–1248":"1168–1248","1120–Male":"1120–Kuollut","1120–Female":"1120–Kuollut","1248":"1248","1168":"1168","1200":"1200","1120":"1120","1140":"1140","Thorpe Manor, Tattershall, Lincolnshire, England":"Tattershall, Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Ashwellthorpe, Norfolk, England":"Ashwellthorpe, Norfolk, England","Thorpe, Lincolnshire, England":"Thorpe St Peter, Lincolnshire, England"},"fr":{"1140–1200":"1140–1200","–Female":"Décédée","1168–1248":"1168–1248","1120–Male":"1120–Décédé","1120–Female":"1120–Décédée","1248":"1248","1168":"1168","1200":"1200","1120":"1120","1140":"1140","Thorpe Manor, Tattershall, Lincolnshire, England":"Tattershall, Lincolnshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Ashwellthorpe, Norfolk, England":"Ashwellthorpe, Norfolk, Angleterre","Thorpe, Lincolnshire, England":"Thorpe St Peter, Lincolnshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Hugh John de Thorpe est né en 1140, à Tattershall, Lincolnshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son père, Robert de Thorpe, avait 21 ans et sa mère, Eda De Thorpe, avait 21 ans. Il a épousé Unknown. Il est décédé en 1200, à Thorpe St Peter, Lincolnshire, Angleterre, à l’âge de 60 ans."},"de":{"1140–1200":"1140–1200","–Female":"Verstorben","1168–1248":"1168–1248","1120–Male":"1120–Verstorben","1120–Female":"1120–Verstorben","1248":"1248","1168":"1168","1200":"1200","1120":"1120","1140":"1140","Thorpe Manor, Tattershall, Lincolnshire, England":"Tattershall, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Ashwellthorpe, Norfolk, England":"Ashwellthorpe, Norfolk, England","Thorpe, Lincolnshire, England":"Thorpe St Peter, Lincolnshire, England","lifeSummary":"Als Hugh John de Thorpe 1140 in Tattershall, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom geboren wurde, war sein Vater Robert de Thorpe 21 und seine Mutter Eda De Thorpe 21. Er hat Unknown geheiratet. Er starb 1200 im Alter von 60 Jahren in Thorpe St Peter, Lincolnshire, England."},"ht":{"1140–1200":"1140–1200","–Female":"Desede","1168–1248":"1168–1248","1120–Male":"1120–Desede","1120–Female":"1120–Desede","1248":"1248","1168":"1168","1200":"1200","1120":"1120","1140":"1140","Thorpe Manor, Tattershall, Lincolnshire, England":"Tattershall, Lincolnshire, Angletè, United Kingdom","Ashwellthorpe, Norfolk, England":"Ashwellthorpe, Norfolk, England",